steps.content:
Combining these steps gives us the complete algorithm. This structure is a fundamental part of **Topic 4.3.5 (Algorithms with Loops and Branching)**. 

```java
int min = numbers[0];
for (int i = 1; i < numbers.length; i++) {
    if (numbers[i] < min) {
        min = numbers[i];
    }
}
```

This code is robust and will work for any non-empty array of integers!

Combining these steps into the final Java-style code gives us the solution for finding the minimum using the enhanced for loop approach:

```java
int min = numbers[0];
for (int n : numbers) {
    if (n < min) {
        min = n;
    }
}
```

This solution effectively manages the search and earns all 4 marks by following the logic of **Topic 4.3.5: Algorithms with Loops and Branching**.

Combining these steps, we get the complete code. Note that for IB exams, you earn marks for the initialization, the loop structure, the comparison, and the update logic.

```java
int min = numbers[0];
int i = 1;
while (i < numbers.length) {
    if (numbers[i] < min) {
        min = numbers[i];
    }
    i++;
}
```

